<body>
  <header>
    <h1>Black Sea — strategic chokepoint</h1>
    <p class="lead">Why this basin matters for trade, energy and security.</p>
  </header>

  <main>
    <article class="card">
      <section>
        <h2>What’s the point?</h2>
        <p>
          The Black Sea connects grain/edible oils markets, energy routes and shipping lanes of Europe, Asia and MENA.
          Before the war, <strong>Russia + Ukraine</strong> together accounted for about
          <strong>34% of global wheat exports</strong>, <strong>17% of corn</strong> and
          <strong>~75% of sunflower oil</strong> (FAO). Disruptions to shipping or higher insurance premia
          quickly spill into food prices.
        </p>
        <p class="pill">Source: FAO/FAOSTAT (shares)</p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Trade & food</h2>
        <p>
          In 2022–2023, the <em>Black Sea Grain Initiative</em> enabled exports of roughly
          <strong>32.9 million tonnes</strong> of cargo (mainly corn and wheat), easing pressure in grains and veg-oils.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Price channel:</strong> resuming sailings lowered risk premia; import access improved for MENA/EU.</li>
          <li><strong>Route:</strong> UA ports → Bosporus → Med → MENA/EU — short sea leg.</li>
          <li><strong>Insurance:</strong> when tensions rise, <em>war-risk</em> premia and banking requirements (LCs, clauses) increase.</li>
        </ul>
        <ul class="sources">
          <li><a href="https://www.ifpri.org/blog/black-sea-grain-initiative-what-it-and-what-did-it-accomplish" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
            IFPRI — What the Black Sea Grain Initiative did (≈32.9 Mt)
          </a></li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Energy</h2>
        <p>
          The region also hosts fuel/LNG terminals in Türkiye and gas pipelines from Russia to TR/EU.
          <strong>TurkStream</strong> capacity is <strong>31.5 bcm/year</strong> (≈ half for TR, half to EU via BG–RS–HU).
          With EU gas demand around <strong>~326–330 bcm in 2023</strong>, that’s a <strong>low-single-digit share</strong>
          overall, yet strategically relevant for transit states and local consumers.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Flows & policy:</strong> the Montreux Convention governs warship straits transit; incidents raise risk.</li>
          <li><strong>Substitution:</strong> LNG plus TR routes reduce parts of EU exposure to other corridors.</li>
        </ul>
        <ul class="sources">
          <li><a href="https://turkstream.info/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">TurkStream — official project site</a></li>
          <li><a href="https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2024/01/16/eu-energy-in-2023/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
            Council of the EU — Energy in 2023 (demand context)
          </a></li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="wrap">
        <h2>So what in practice?</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Food prices:</strong> resumed sailings → relief in grain/veg-oil indices; new shocks → spikes.</li>
          <li><strong>Freight & insurance:</strong> NAVTEX/NOTAM warnings and incidents push up <em>war-risk</em> and freight.</li>
          <li><strong>Risk pass-through:</strong> shipowners/banks/insurers pass premia into end prices.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="cols">
        <div class="wrap">
          <h3 class="good">Pros / opportunities</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Higher capacity & predictability of sea lanes (more stable prices, lower risk premia).</li>
            <li>Logistics diversification (TR, LNG, alternates) trims exposure to single chokepoints.</li>
            <li>Better trade finance & insurance coordination (easier supply-chain funding).</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="wrap">
          <h3 class="bad">Cons / risks</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>War-risk/freight jumps after incidents; potential port downtime.</li>
            <li>Escalation can again restrict grain availability → higher food basket prices.</li>
            <li>Straits chokepoints (Bosporus/Dardanelles) — bunching and delays.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </section>

